Predicting Housing Price with Multiple Linear Regression

By Benjamin Chao

February 26, 2017

First, let us load the data and necessary packages:

Question 1. Make a labeled histogram (with 30 bins) of the ages of the houses in the data set, and describe the distribution.

ames_train$Year.Built <- as.numeric(ames_train$Year.Built)
ames_train$Yr.Sold <- as.numeric(ames_train$Yr.Sold)

ames_train$Age <- ames_train$Yr.Sold - ames_train$Year.Built 

ggplot(data = ames_train, aes(x=ames_train$Age)) +
  geom_histogram(fill="#FF6666", col=I("white")) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = median(ames_train$Age)), colour="black", linetype = "dashed") +  
  annotate("text", x = median(ames_train$Age) * 1.5, y = 125,
                 label = paste0("Median Age:", median(ames_train$Age))) +
  labs(title = "Age of the House") +
  labs(x = "Age", y = "Count")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

summary(ames_train$Age)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    0.00    7.00   33.00   35.56   52.00  136.00

For the analysis, Ive defined the age of house to be the differece between the year of house was sold (Yr.Sold) and the year of the house was built (Year.Built). After all, our data set contains houses that were sold between 2006 and 2010.

As we can see from the histogram, the distribution is multimodal with a few data points that could potentially be outliers. In this case, the median is a more sensible measure of central tendency.

The median suggests that half of sample is aged under 33 while the other half is aged between 34 and 136! The mode also shows that over 150 houses or 15% of the houses are either brand new or less than one year old. There also seems to be a few outliers that are over 100 years old.

Question 2. The mantra in real estate is Location, Location, Location! Make a graphical display that relates a home price to its neighborhood in Ames, Iowa. Which summary statistics are most appropriate to use for determining the most expensive, least expensive, and most heterogeneous (having the most variation in housing price) neighborhoods? Report which neighborhoods these are based on the summary statistics of your choice. Report the value of your chosen summary statistics for these neighborhoods.

ames_train$price <- as.numeric(ames_train$price)

ames_train %>% select(Neighborhood, price) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(factor(Neighborhood), price)) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(color = factor(Neighborhood)),fill=NA) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust =1)) +
  scale_y_discrete(name="House Price") +
  xlab('Neighborhoods') + 
  theme(legend.position='none') +
  coord_flip()

We can easily see from the plot that there are outliers in almost all the neighborhoods in our sample. Again, I will use IQR as the summary statistics. Remember, the advantage of the median is that its not adversely influenced by extreme values (outliers). For this same reason, the National Association of Realtors in the United States has been using this measure to discuss property prices in their public communication.

Three quick observations can be made here: 1) StoneBr has the higest median housing price ($340,691.5), 2) MeadowV has the lowest median housing price ($85,750) and 3) either StoneBr or NridgHt could have the most heterogeneous housing prices.

To determine the most heterogeneous neighborhood, we need to compare their standard deviation. It turns out StoneBr has the highest Std of 123,459.10 and thus its our most heterogeneous neighborhood.

The values of median housing and Standard Deviation for each of the three neighborhood are listed below.

ames_train %>%
  group_by(Neighborhood) %>%
  filter(Neighborhood %in% c("StoneBr","MeadowV","NridgHt")) %>%
  summarize(MedianPrice = median(price),  StandardDeviation = sd(price))
## # A tibble: 3  3

Question 3. Which variable has the largest number of missing values? Explain why it makes sense that there are so many missing values for this variable.

miss <- colSums(is.na(ames_train))

head(sort(miss,decreasing=TRUE), n = 1)
## Pool.QC 
##     997

On the surface, Pool.QC seems like a variable with the largest number of NA or missing values. However, a quick look at the code book and we would learn that NA simply means the house has no backyard pool. So, our sample would tell us that the majority of houses in Ames, Iowa dont have backyard pool. Does our sample statistics make sense in the real-world context? Lets do a quick research and find out!

According to Realtor.com, top 10 medium-to-large cities with the highest percentage of backyard pools are all in the states that have warm weather throughout the entire year, such as Texas, California, Arizon and Florida. Click here for link

In contrast, the annual high temerate in Ames is only 59 degree in Fahrenheit (F) with average snallfall of 31 inches every year. Click here for link. Given these background information, we can safely conclude that our sample statistics are not far off from reality.

Question 4. We want to predict the natural log of the home prices. Candidate explanatory variables are lot size in square feet (Lot.Area), slope of property (Land.Slope), original construction date (Year.Built), remodel date (Year.Remod.Add), and the number of bedrooms above grade (Bedroom.AbvGr). Pick a model selection or model averaging method covered in the Specialization, and describe how this method works. Then, use this method to find the best multiple regression model for predicting the natural log of the home prices.

Data1 <- select(ames_train, Lot.Area, Land.Slope, Year.Built, Year.Remod.Add, Bedroom.AbvGr, price)

mod1 <- lm(log(price) ~., data=Data1, na.action=na.exclude)
summary(mod1)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = log(price) ~ ., data = Data1, na.action = na.exclude)
##

## Multiple R-squared:  0.5625, Adjusted R-squared:  0.5598 
## F-statistic: 212.8 on 6 and 993 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

I choose backward selection of variables that optimize Adjusted R-squared to build our model. Under this approach, I start with fitting a model with all the variables of interest. Then the least significant variable is dropped, so long as it is not significant at our chosen critical level or 0.05. I continue by successively re-fitting reduced models and applying the same rule until all remaining variables are statistically significant.

Much to my surprise, all five of the given predictors are deemed to be significant in our initial model. Thus, I will use the entire set of predictors in the model for the on-going analysis.

So far, we know that observation No.428 has the largest squared residual and has the lowest housing price of $12,789. In our sample of 1,000 houses, the median housing price is $159,467 and even the lower 25% (or the 1st quartile) can fetch a price of $129,762.

When comparing the 5 characteristics (Lot.Area, Land.Slop, Year.Built, Year.Remod.Add,and Bedroom.AbvGr) of house No.428 with that of the overall sample, I found out that its Lot.Area, Year.Built and Bedroom.AbvGr all have unusually low values. Thus, these 3 relevant factors could have contributed to the high squared residual for house No.428.

Question 6. Use the same model selection method you chose in Question 4 to again find the best multiple regression model to predict the natural log of home prices, but this time replacing Lot.Area with log(Lot.Area). Do you arrive at a model including the same set of predictors?

Data2 <- select(ames_train, Lot.Area, Land.Slope, Year.Built, Year.Remod.Add, Bedroom.AbvGr, price)

mod2 <- lm(log(price) ~ log(Lot.Area) + Land.Slope + Year.Built + Year.Remod.Add + Bedroom.AbvGr, data=Data2, na.action=na.exclude)
summary(mod2)

Question 7. Do you think it is better to log transform Lot.Area, in terms of assumptions for linear regression? Make graphs of the predicted values of log home price versus the true values of log home price for the regression models selected for Lot.Area and log(Lot.Area). Referencing these two plots, provide a written support that includes a quantitative justification for your answer in the first part of question 7.

plot(predict(mod1),log(Data1$price), col="#E69F00", main="Predicted vs Actual Value - with Lot.Area",
     xlab="predicted",ylab="actual")
abline(a=0,b=1)

plot(predict(mod2),log(Data2$price), col="#56B4E9", main="Predicted vs Actual Value - with log(Lot.Area)", xlab="predicted",ylab="actual")
abline(a=0,b=1)

In conclusion, I think its better to log transform Lot.Area because log transforming yields a stronger correlation!

The model with log(Lot.Area) looks very accurate as most data points are closely clustered around the best-fit line. We can clearly see a strong correlation between the models predictions and the actual observations.

However, the model with regular values of Lot.Area is the exact opposite. The linear relationship looks like it might easily be weakened by simple removal of few outliers.
